instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows the MBSE development hierarchy described in the documents: it starts with a requirements model, proceeds to functional‑architecture models, then logical‑architecture models, and finally to the product/technical layer. At each stage the Twin is represented with appropriate artifacts – SysML requirement diagrams, SysML internal‑block diagrams or IBDs for functional and logical structures, and concrete component‑connector models in ADLs (e.g., ACME, AADL, MontiArc) for the technical layer. Transition between stages is managed by concretizing the Digital Shadow Reference Model into a concrete realization (a mapping of reference concepts to concrete classes and associations) and by extending the model with simulation or calculation models (e.g., Simulink) that generate data traces. Governance is achieved through the reference‑model conformance relation that defines which concrete models are admissible at each lifecycle phase."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "The approach stresses traceability of every model element back to its source data and verification of model transformations (e.g., from SysML architectural models to simulation models) to preserve semantics. Fidelity is addressed by combining physics‑based (white‑box) models with data‑driven (black‑box) components, thereby leveraging the predictability of analytical models and the expressive power of machine‑learning models. Validation relies on the correctness of the underlying models and on systematic verification methods proposed in the literature, which aim to ensure that the digital representation accurately reflects the physical system."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The approach relies on a reference‑model based standardisation strategy: a Digital Shadow Reference Model defines domain concepts and a formal conformance relation that identifies all admissible concrete models. Modelling is performed with standard languages and standards – SysML for system modelling, ADLs such as ACME, AADL and MontiArc for component‑connector architecture, and simulation tools like Simulink for behavior. The concrete realization of the reference model follows a mapping (conformance) to these standard artefacts, ensuring interoperability and compliance with the established modelling standards."
]
